<!-- Lesson 2-2: Vigenère Cipher -->
<div id="lesson2-2-content">
    <p class="mb-4">The Vigenère cipher is a method of encrypting text by using a series of different Caesar ciphers based on the letters of a keyword. It was first described by Giovan Battista Bellaso in 1553, but later misattributed to Blaise de Vigenère who published a stronger autokey cipher in 1586.</p>
    
    <div class="key-concept mb-5">
        <h4><i class="fas fa-key"></i> Key Concept</h4>
        <p>The Vigenère cipher uses a keyword to determine multiple shift values, making it significantly stronger than the Caesar cipher. Each letter of the keyword specifies a different shift amount for each corresponding letter in the plaintext.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="lesson-section mb-5">
        <h3 class="section-title">How It Works</h3>
        
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column">
                <h4 class="subsection-title">Encryption Process</h4>
                <ol class="process-list">
                    <li>Choose a keyword (e.g., "KEY")</li>
                    <li>Repeat the keyword to match the length of the plaintext</li>
                    <li>For each letter in the plaintext:
                        <ul>
                            <li>Find the corresponding keyword letter</li>
                            <li>Use the position of the keyword letter in the alphabet (A=0, B=1, ..., Z=25) as the shift value</li>
                            <li>Shift the plaintext letter by this amount (using the Caesar cipher method)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                
                <div class="formula-box">
                    <h5>Mathematical Representation:</h5>
                    <p>For each plaintext letter p at position i, the ciphertext letter c is:</p>
                    <div class="formula">c<sub>i</sub> = (p<sub>i</sub> + k<sub>i mod m</sub>) % 26</div>
                    <p>where k is the keyword converted to numbers, and m is the length of the keyword</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="column">
                <h4 class="subsection-title">Example: Keyword "KEY"</h4>
                <div class="cipher-example">
