<!-- Lesson 2-3: Substitution Cipher -->
<div id="lesson2-3-content">
    <p class="mb-4">A substitution cipher is an encryption method where each letter in the plaintext is replaced by another letter or symbol according to a fixed system. Unlike the Caesar cipher which uses a shift pattern, a substitution cipher can use any arbitrary replacement pattern.</p>
    
    <div class="key-concept mb-5">
        <h4><i class="fas fa-key"></i> Key Concept</h4>
        <p>In a simple substitution cipher, each letter of the alphabet is mapped to a different letter or symbol. This mapping forms the encryption key. The same substitution is used throughout the entire message.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="lesson-section mb-5">
        <h3 class="section-title">How It Works</h3>
        
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column">
                <h4 class="subsection-title">Encryption Process</h4>
                <ol class="process-list">
                    <li>Create a substitution key - a mapping of each letter to its replacement</li>
                    <li>For each letter in the plaintext, replace it with its corresponding letter or symbol from the key</li>
                    <li>Non-alphabetic characters can either remain unchanged or have their own substitutions</li>
                </ol>
                
                <div class="note-box">
                    <p><strong>Key Space:</strong> With 26 letters in the English alphabet, there are 26! (factorial) possible keys - approximately 4.03 × 10²⁶ different possible arrangements.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="column">
                <h4 class="subsection-title">Example Substitution</h4>
                <div class="cipher-example">
